<Heading Level="HeadingLevel.H2">Container Component</Heading>
<Paragraph>
    Containers are the most basic layout element in Bootstrap and are required when using our default grid system.
    Containers are used to contain, pad, and (sometimes) center the content within them. While containers can be
    nested, most layouts do not require a nested container.
</Paragraph>

<DocsSection ComponentName="Container"></DocsSection>


<Heading Id="basic-containers" IsAnchor="true" Level="HeadingLevel.H3" MarginTop="@marginTop">Basic Containers</Heading>
<Paragraph>
    A container is either fixed-width with a maximum width set at each breakpoint. A container can also be fluid
    to have 100% width at all breakpoints. <WikiLink Page="Container" Section="basic-containers"></WikiLink>
</Paragraph>

<Container Type="ContainerType.FixedWidth" Padding="Spacing.S3" MarginTop="Spacing.S3" BorderColor="NamedColor.Dark" BackgroundColor="NamedColor.Light">Fixed-Width Container</Container>
<Container Type="ContainerType.Fluid" Padding="Spacing.S3" MarginTop="Spacing.S3" BorderColor="NamedColor.Dark" BackgroundColor="NamedColor.Light">Fluid Container</Container>


<Heading Id="responsive-containers" IsAnchor="true" Level="HeadingLevel.H3" MarginTop="@marginTop">Responsive Containers</Heading>
<Paragraph>
    Containers can also be responsive. A responsive container is 100% wide at or below the specified breakpoint, and turns to a fixed-width container above.
    <WikiLink Page="Container" Section="responsive-containers"></WikiLink>
</Paragraph>

